data.name: richTextBox1.Text
data.value:
On first use you will need to enter your scopes Focal Length & Diameter in metres and your cameras Pixel Size in microns. Further uses of the application will automatically populate these fields with the last used entries.
If your focusing system causes the OTA to rotate, check the option 'Rotating Focuser'.
Place a checkmark against the relevant filter that you are using, either Red, Green or Blue, or all three if you're using a OSC camera.
If you wish, you can check the option to play a sound when best focus is achieved.
Place the Tri-Bahtinov mask on your OTA.
Making sure that you have a suitable star centered in your FOV.
Press the 'Set Capture Area' button.
Using your mouses left button and starting from the center, drag a selection box around the focusing star and then release.
An image of the focusing star will now be loaded in Tri-Bahtinov Grabber for analysis.
The image is almost instantly analysed and inforamtion regarding it's focus will be displayed.
While making the adjustments as laid out below, remember to keep the focus star centered in the FOV.
Make any adjustments to your focus as necessary to get to the best possible focus i.e. smallest error readouts.
Next cover 2 of the 3 sections of the Tri-Bahtinov mask and concentrate on getting this single remaining section as the best focus you possibly can.
Now move the mask cover to cover the section you have just got to focus plus one other and by tweaking the collimation screws, make very small adjustments to bring the uncovered section to best possible focus, do not use your focuser.
Once again, move the mask cover to cover the first and second areas that you have just adjusted, leaving the last section open.
Again, using the collimation screws and not the focuser, make small adjustments to get this final section in as perfect alignment as you can.
Remove the mask cover and check the readouts, if in any doubt about the quality of the focus you can repeat the above adjustments steps once again.
When you are happy with the focus, remove the Tri-Bahtinov mask and feel free to check to make sure there are nice concentric rings on the slightly defocused star. 'Al's Collimation Aid' is a nice free tool for doing this.
